25|$|In 977 a Turkic {{governor}} of the Samanids, Sabuktigin, conquered Ghazna (in present-day Afghanistan) and established a dynasty, the Ghaznavids, that lasted to 1186. The Ghaznavid empire grew by taking all of the Samanid territories south of the Amu Darya {{in the last decade}} of the 10th century, and eventually occupied parts of <b>Eastern</b> Iran, <b>Afghanistan,</b> Pakistan and northwest India.|$|R
